at it procures through its “ancillary services” markets to preserve the critical balance of supply and demand as well as the power quality on the grid. For example, the grid needs resources in reserve to deal with unexpected and sudden events, like a generator outage. SPP has markets for supplemental reserve and spinning reserve products to meet this need. Supplemental reserves markets procure power from  ...    ### Q. Who participates in SPP’s matters? A. Active participants are frequently those companies and organizations who pay an annual fee to become SPP members. Members have voting and other rights of participation in SPP stakeholder processes, committees, and working groups. SPP has 110 members as of September 2023, including power producers, investor-owned and municipal utilities, cooperatives,  ...    is next discussed, a subset of the members forms a key SPP Committee called the Members Committee, which reports  ...    SPP’s RSC has arguably the most influence of any similar committee in any RTO/ISO, such that decision-making power is essentially shared between the SPP Board and RSC, depending on the issue. Under SPP’s Regional State Committee Bylaws,[9] the RSC has the primary responsibility for electric resource adequacy (ensuring that there are adequate electric power resources to meet demand) across the entire region. The RSC also has primary responsibility for: - allocation of assets called “financial transmission rights,” among other responsibilities. - cost allocation for transmission upgrades, and - determining whether remote resources will be included in the regional transmission plan, Thus, the states participating in SPP have, through the RSC, retained responsibility over some key issues in SPP that  ...    ### Q. What stakeholder processes does SPP have?\n\nA. Like"
